<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-12-19T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-12-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="139" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/220</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-19T18:00:00+00:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">December 19, 1916, 6 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 20, 8.10 a.
                                m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>5343. Your circular December 16, 5 p. m.<note n="1" xml:id="d139fn1">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_94">p.
                                94</ref>.</note> Lord <persName>Robert Cecil</persName> has just
                            informed me that the British Government will decline the German proposal
                            to discuss peace because it contains no concrete terms with which such a
                            discussion might begin and for other reasons; and that the Prime
                            Minister will set forth the Government’s position in full in the speech
                            which he is now delivering in the House of Commons.</p>
                        <p>I will telegraph the text of what the Prime Minister says at the earliest
                            hour possible.</p>
                        <p>Lord <persName corresp="#p_CEARV1">Robert</persName> informed me that the
                            British Government had requested the French Government to draw up the
                            reply of the Allies to the note of the Central powers.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>